== Reception and legacy ==
''Barbarian''{{'}}s advertisements triggered some outcries of moral indignation. ''[[Electron User]]''  reported that another magazine had refused to publish [[Superior Software]]'s advert for its licensed BBC Micro and Acorn Electron ports unless parts of the image were covered up.<ref name='electronuserjuly88'>{{cite magazine |title=Advert eyeful|magazine=Electron User|volume=5 |issue=9 |publisher=Database |date=July 1988 |page=5}}</ref> ''Electron User'', who published the uncensored advertisement,<ref name='electronusersept88'>{{cite magazine |title=Barbarian starts a real life battle|magazine=Electron User|volume=5 |issue=12 |publisher=Database |date=September 1988 |page=6}}</ref> received letters from readers and religious bodies, who called the image "offensive and particularly insulting to women" and an "ugly pornographic advertisement".<ref name=retro23 /> Richard Hanson, Superior's managing director commented that the [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] had confirmed that the image was not in bad taste,<ref name='electronusersept88' /> and that the publicity was likely to send the game to the top of the charts.<ref name='electronuserjuly88' />

Chris Jager, a writer for ''[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]'', considered the cover "a trashy controversy-magnet featuring a glamour-saucepot" and a "big bloke [in leotard]".<ref>{{cite web  | last = Jager  | first = Chris  | title = The Hottest—and Most Hideous—Video Game Box Art Ever  | work = [[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]  | publisher = [[International Data Group|IDG]]  | date = 2009-02-28  | url = http://www.pcworld.com/article/160321/the_hottest_and_most_hideous_video_game_box_art_ever.html
  | access-date = 2009-12-15 }}</ref>

Video game industry observers Russell DeMaria and Johnny Wilson commented that the United Kingdom public were more concerned over the scantily-clad Whittaker than the gory contents in the game.<ref>{{cite book  | last1 = DeMaria  | first1 = Russell  | last2 = Wilson  | first2 = Johnny  | title = High Score!: The Illustrated History of Electronic Games  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HJNvZLvpCEQC  | access-date = 2009-12-14  | edition = Second  | year = 2004  | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]]/Osborne  | location = California, United States   | isbn = 0-07-223172-6  | page = 356  | chapter = Across the Atlantic  | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HJNvZLvpCEQC&pg=PA320 }}</ref>

In 1988, ''[[ACE (magazine)|Advanced Computer Entertainment]]'' magazine submitted videos of the gameplay to the [[British Board of Film Classification]] who stated that the decapitations were merely "storybook violence" and that the game would have probably have received a PG certificate had it been submitted to them.<ref name='ace5arethesegamesillegal'>{{cite magazine |title=Are These Games Illegal?|magazine=ACE|issue=5|publisher=Future Publishing|date=February 1988|page=27|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=1731&page=28|access-date=28 January 2023}}</ref> David Houghton, writer for ''[[GamesRadar]]'', claimed the game would be rated "Mature" by the [[Entertainment Software Rating Board]] if it was published in 2009.<ref>{{cite web
