''[[Popular Computing Weekly]]'' considered the Amstrad version to be the best, calling the Commodore 64's animation "shaky".<ref name='pcw5jan87c64ams' /> ''[[Your Sinclair]]'', awarding the game 7/10, complained it was too similar to previous games like ''[[The Way of the Exploding Fist]]'' and ''[[Ninja (1986 video game)|Ninja]]''.<ref name='ys19' />

According to Leinfellner, the controversy did not negatively affect ''Barbarian'', but boosted the game's sales and profile tremendously.<ref name=retro23 /> The game proved to be a big hit, reaching the top of the all-format charts in 1987<ref name='pcw19june87charts'>{{cite magazine |title=Top Twenty|magazine=Popular Computing Weekly|issue=24|publisher=Sunshine Publications|date=19 June 1987|page=53|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=2963&page=53|access-date=28 January 2023}}</ref> and number one in the Acorn Electron chart in 1988.<ref name='electronusersept88charts'>{{cite magazine |title=Gallup Software Chart|magazine=Electron User|volume=5 |issue=12 |publisher=Database |date=September 1988 |page=4}}</ref> Leinfellner said he received royalty cheques for approximately seven years, the first of which was for [[Pound sterling|£]]20,000.<ref name=russell /> ''[[Barbarian II: The Dungeon of Drax]]'' was released in 1988, and ''Barbarian III'' was in the works.<ref name=retro23 /> Van Wijk and Whittaker were hired again to grace the box cover and advertisements.<ref>{{cite journal
  | last = Boughton
  | first = Paul
  |date=May 1990
  | title = The Axe Man Cometh
  | journal = Computer and Video Games
  | issue = 81
  | pages = 100–101
  | publisher = Dennis Publishing
  | location = London, United Kingdom
  | issn = 0261-3697 }}</ref> After the success with ''Barbarian'', Palace Software began to expand its portfolio by publishing games that were created by other developers. ''Barbarian'', however, remained its most popular game, best remembered for its violent sword fights and Maria Whittaker.<ref name=retro23 />

In 2011, [[Anuman Interactive]] (French publisher) launched a remake of the game, adapted to mobile devices and computers: ''Barbarian – The Death Sword''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macgasm.net/news/gaming-news/microids-and-anuman-interactive-bring-barbarian-the-death-sword-to-ios-coming-to-mac-this-march/|title=Microids and Anuman Interactive bring Barbarian – The Death Sword to iOS, coming to Mac this March|first=Elle|last=Cooke|date=February 29, 2012|website=Macgasm}}</ref>

A spiritual successor, ''Age of Barbarian'', was released in 2012 by Italian [[indie game]] developer Crian Soft, with a much longer and updated Extended Cut released in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/402880/Age_of_Barbarian_Extended_Cut/ |title=Age of Barbarian Extended Cut |publisher=Steam }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.criansoft.com/age-of-barbarians-extended-cut.html |title=Age of Barbarian Extended Cut |publisher=Crian Soft }}</ref>

